intimately engaged themselves with works of art and architecture on a daily basis. This book examines how viewers in Medicean Florence were self-consciously cultivated to enhance their sensory appreciation of works of art and creatively self-fashion through somaesthetic experience. Mobilized as a technology for the production of knowledge with and through their bodies, viewers contributed to the essential meaning of Renaissance art and, in the process, bound them to others. By investigating the framework and practice of somaesthetic viewing of works by Benozzo Gozzoli, Donatello, Benedetto Buglioni, Giorgio Vasari, and others in fifteenth- and sixteenth-century Florence, the book approaches the viewer as a powerful tool that was used by patrons to shape identity and power in the Renaissance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArtzItalyzFlorencexHistoryy15th century. 0aArtzItalyzFlorencexHistoryy16th century. 0aRenaissancezItalyzFlorence. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aFlorentine art.  aMedici patronage.  aPolitical persuasion.  aRenaissance viewers.  aSomaesthetics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2020z9783110704655oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2020 Englishz978311070